================================================================================
5. Caveats / follow-ups (NOT failures of this drill, but real ops notes)
================================================================================

  - `pg_dump --no-privileges` strips GRANT statements. On a production
    restore, the `matgary_app` NOSUPERUSER role must be recreated AND
    granted SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE on every tenant-scoped table BEFORE
    the app can connect. `infra/init-postgres.sql` creates the role on a
    FRESH container boot but does NOT regrant after a restore — the
    production restore runbook needs both steps explicitly.
  - This drill targeted the latest daily dump. weekly-*.sql.gz dumps were
    not exercised. Same format, expected to behave identically — but a
    follow-up drill should cover both rotations once per quarter.
  - Off-site shipping path (`BACKUP_REMOTE_HOOK`) is not configured and is
    out of scope for this drill.
  - The throwaway container had no persistent volume; everything was wiped
    on `docker rm -f`. No risk of cross-contamination with the live DB.

================================================================================
6. Reproduction commands (exact)
================================================================================

  docker run --rm -d --name pg-restore-test \
    -e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=test \
    -p 55432:5432 \
    -v $PWD/backups:/backups:ro \
    -v $PWD/infra/restore.sh:/usr/local/bin/restore.sh:ro \
    postgres:16-alpine

  docker exec pg-restore-test psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE matgary_restore;"

  docker exec \
    -e PGHOST=localhost -e PGUSER=postgres -e PGPASSWORD=test \
    -e PGDATABASE=matgary_restore -e RESTORE_CONFIRM=1 \
    pg-restore-test sh /usr/local/bin/restore.sh \
    /backups/daily-2026-06-01T02-30-00Z.sql.gz

  docker rm -f pg-restore-test
